{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17619799","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17619799"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:36:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:36:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16578"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16578","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16578"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.33,0.31,0.24,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9269"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75960"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9269","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9269"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16578"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61461"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"2443"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"9872"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21957"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21960"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75960","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75960"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECerebral perfusion pressure (CPP) is an important physiological parameter that must be maintained to ensure adequate brain tissue oxygenation. CPP is the result of subtracting intracranial pressure (ICP) from mean arterial pressure (MAP), i.e. CPP = MAP - ICP. It can therefore be improved by either increasing MAP or decreasing ICP.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following agents best increases cerebral perfusion pressure through direct effects on systemic blood pressure?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Dexamethasone","Hypertonic saline","Mannitol","Metaraminol","Temporary hyperventilation"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Emetaraminol\u003C/strong\u003E, which is a vasopressor that directly increases systemic blood pressure through alpha-adrenergic stimulation. This increases the MAP and therefore the CPP. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options work through different mechanisms:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDexamethasone\u003C/strong\u003E reduces ICP by decreasing vasogenic oedema, and is not used to directly increase MAP \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypertonic saline\u003C/strong\u003E creates an osmotic gradient to reduce cerebral oedema, thereby reducing ICP and improving CPP\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMannitol\u003C/strong\u003E is an osmotic diuretic that reduces intracranial pressure by drawing water out of the brain, working like hypertonic saline to decrease ICP and therefore improve CPP\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETemporary hyperventilation\u003C/strong\u003E causes cerebral vasoconstriction which reduces ICP, again improving CPP in this way\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile all these interventions may help maintain CPP, only metaraminol works primarily by increasing systemic blood pressure to achieve this.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cerebral perfusion pressure (CPP) is calculated as mean arterial pressure (MAP) minus intracranial pressure (ICP).","Vasopressors like metaraminol increase mean arterial pressure (MAP) and therefore improve cerebral perfusion pressure (CPP).","Agents like mannitol and hypertonic saline work to decrease intracranial pressure (ICP) in order to help maintain cerebral perfusion pressure (CPP)."],"references":["Kareemi H, Pratte M, English S, Hendin A. Initial Diagnosis and Management of Acutely Elevated Intracranial Pressure. J Intensive Care Med. 2023 Jul;38(7):643-650. doi: 10.1177/08850666231156589. Epub 2023 Feb 19. PMID: 36802976; PMCID: PMC10302390.","Peng, L., Guo, D., Shi, Y. et al. The incidence, risk factors and outcomes of impaired cerebral autoregulation in aortic arch surgery: a single-center, retrospective cohort study. J Cardiothorac Surg 18, 312 (2023). https://doi.org/10.1186/s13019-023-02413-z","Han P, Zhou Y. Safety and efficacy of peripheral metaraminol infusion in patients with neurological conditions: a single-center retrospective observational study. Front Neurol. 2024 Jun 3;15:1398827. doi: 10.3389/fneur.2024.1398827. PMID: 38887388; PMCID: PMC11180898."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61461"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16578"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61461","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61461"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T17:35:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T17:36:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9269"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75960"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.eme